  1. Q: Split the sample into two random samples sizes 70% and 30%.
  2. Q: Perform prinicipal components of variables 1:7 from the GermanCredit Data on training sample.
data(GermanCredit)
GermanCredit <- data.frame(scale(GermanCredit[,1:7]))
german.credit.train_ind <- sample(1:(nrow(GermanCredit)),700)
german.credit_1to7.train <- data.frame(scale(GermanCredit[german.credit.train_ind,]))
german.credit_1to7.mean <- apply(german.credit_1to7.train,2,mean)
german.credit_1to7.sd <- apply(german.credit_1to7.train,2,sd)
german.credit_1to7.train <- (german.credit_1to7.train-german.credit_1to7.mean)/german.credit_1to7.sd
x = prcomp(german.credit_1to7.train)
  1. Generate Scree Plots and select number of components you would retain. From the scree plot below, we can see the “elbow” at around 6 Loadings which means we will keep 6 loadings for our analysis.
cum.VAF.gm1 <- data.frame("Number_of_Components" = c(seq(1,7)), "VAF" = (c(x$sdev^2)/sum(x$sdev^2)))
ggplot(cum.VAF.gm1, aes(x=Number_of_Components, y=VAF, colours = VAF))  + ggtitle("Varaince accounted for by individual loadings for Train.") + geom_line(data = cum.VAF.gm1, aes(x=Number_of_Components, y=VAF), color = 'red', size = 3)

Q4) Plot component 1 loadings (x-axis) versus Component 2 loadings (y-axis). Use this plot to interpret and name the components.

A:
For the 1st component against the 2nd component, The 1st component has a very strong positive effect on Duration and Amount. The first component has a near 0 effect on 4 of the paramters which are Age, Number of Existing Credits, Duration of Residence, and Number of People Maintenance. The second component has a positive effect on all paramters except for Duration.

For the 1st component against the 3rd component, the 1st component, again, has a very strong positive effect on Amount and Duration. The 1st component also has 4 paramters on it’s 0 axis, while the second component has 3 parameters above 0 which are Number of People Maintenance, Number of Existing credits and Amount. Duration, Duration of Residence, and installment rate percentage, and Age are all negatively affected by the 3rd comonent.

For the 1st component against the the 4th component,we can see that Number of Existing Credits, Duration, Number of People Maintenance and Duration are all favorable to component 4 while Age and Duration of Residence are unfavorable towards Component 4.

For the 1st component against the 5th, The only parameter that is favorable in the 5th component is Number of Existing credits. Duration, Intallment Rater Percentage, and Number of People Maintenance are all unfavorable towards the 5th component.

For the 1st component against the 6th, The only parameter that is favorable to the 6th component is Duraiton of Residence while Age has an unfavorable effect on the 6th component.

  1. & 8) Perform holdout validation of principal component solution and compute Varriance Account for in the Holdout Sample There is a high correlation of .96 as seen below.
german.Credit_1to7.test <- scale(data.frame(GermanCredit[-german.credit.train_ind,]),
                                 center = colMeans(german.credit_1to7.train),
                                 scale = apply(german.credit_1to7.train, 2, sd))
y=predict(x, newdata = german.Credit_1to7.test)
manual.set <- y[,1:6]%*%t((x$rotation[,1:6]))
round(cor(as.vector(manual.set),as.vector(german.Credit_1to7.test))^2,2)
## [1] 0.96

  1. Plot rotated loadings(1) versus rotated loadings (2) and (3). Do you think Principal Components reduced this data a lot? Do you like the solution?

A: In the visualization with the 1st loading against the 2nd, Age has taken a negative value of 1 relative to the 2nd component while the rest of the parameters have a 0 to near 0 value for the 2nd component. Duration and Amount are favorable to the 1st component while the rest of the parameters have a 0 to near 0 value for the 1st component.

The verimax function has proven itself incredibly useful within this excercise.

For the 1st component against the 2nd component, the verimax function has minimized the 2nd component’s minor to medium effects on Installment Rate Percentage, Number of People Maintenance, Number of Existing Credits, and Duration of Residence while maximizing the ngative effect of Age from -.6 to -1.

For the 2nd component against the 3rd component, the verimax function has minimized the 2nd component’s minor to medium effects on Age, Number of People Maintenance, Number of Existing Credits, and Duration of Residence while maximizing the ngative effect of Installment Rate Percentage from .5 to 1.

The 1st component didn’t seem to change much with the verimax funciton.
